The best meals happen by chance.
Found this roadside kitchen in Antigua and feasted on tender goat curry and BBQ pig tails that melted in my mouth.  Its remarkable what can be done with a grill and a portable burner under a tent. And I had to wash it all down with a bottle of Ting. Going back tomorrow for the Goat Water stew.

This is a sugar apple or sweet sop, a fruit that grows here in Antigua, a member of the genus Annona, which includes other tropical fruits like Cherimoya and Soursop. The sweet, creamy capsule has a perfume flavor that is like a combination of apple, lychee, pineapple and custard. It's such a wild, unique flavor that is not unlike the paw paw fruit that grows wild in the woods of Kentucky.  Turns out they are related.  Makes you take a moment to think about all the flora connections around the world that we don't fully understand.

This is an initiative and a partnership with @leeinitiative @srrj_coalition and @heinz to help black-owned restaurants around the country with grants for their businesses.  Our mission @leeinitiative has always been dedicated to equity and diverity and helping make the industry a little more fair.  When we did some research on how PPP was distributed during the pandemic, it was appalling what the numbers showed on the percentage of black owned businesses that were denied PPP loans. 
I realize that no system is ideal and no solution is perfect, but this is exactly the kind of inequality that hinders our industry and divides our restaurants.  I am proud to announce the winners of the 2022 grants.  I wish them well and much success in the new year. 
And thank you to @heinz for stepping in to support.

It's been a tough year of loss.  This one hurts.  Rest well Chef Jean-Robert de Cavel @jeanro2k 
You have been an inspiration to so many.

Our year @leeinitiative was bookended by 2 massive Kentucky disasters , tornadoes in Western KY and the flooding of Eastern KY, that stretched our resources to the limit.  But we found so much support from our community to keep helping those in dire need. 
In between those tragedies, there was much to be hopeful for.  These are just a few of the programs we were proud to achieve in 2022. 
The team at @leeinitiative is unflinching and dedicated in ways that always astound me. 
As we look ahead to 2023, we are looking for new and creative ways to foster equity and diversity in the restaurant industry.  Thank you to all who support our mission.

A wonderful exploration of Korean food in NYC from traditional to innovative, from Flushing to Koreatown, from humble decor to modern design. I had a flashback to when I was a little kid and my family would go to 32nd street for a meal.  Back then there were only 3 Korean restaurants on that street and it was not exactly a safe neighborhood.  It is astounding to see how far Korean cuisine has come.

Five years ago, we embarked on a journey when we formed The LEE Initiative to lead with kindness, help workers in need, promote diversity and equity, and believe that the impossible is possible. We are always looking ahead to learn, evolve, and be a resource for the people who make up our incredible independent restaurant industry.

We are excited to soon announce the next chapter of The LEE Initiative – a think tank, research and non-profit restaurant based in Washington D.C. We will implement policies and practices that will demonstrate what the future of sustainable restaurants can look like, addressing issues as far ranging as labor practices, climate change, sustainability, innovation, and diversity. We will take a new approach to fine-dining – minimal plastic waste, no gas lines, and a predominantly female staff – while maintaining a level of high quality, to create luxury with social responsibility. The restaurant will partner with a university-backed research program, and our data/findings will be published open source for anyone to access and use. In doing so, we want to give back to our community by sharing data that is needed to ensure that we collectively progress in this industry. It is our love letter to the people who have worked so hard to make our restaurant culture the best it can be.

This is an industry effort, so we welcome your feedback, ideas, and collaboration. For now, this is all we can share about this exciting new project, but stay tuned for more details coming soon.

For partnerships and sponsorship opportunities, please reach out to us via our website LEEinitiative.org.

We are getting close to opening @namisteakhouse and we're ramping up the kimchi making. Incredible day of fishing with my best first mate.  She has gotten so good, she is starting to out fish me.  I did help on the barracuda.  We caught a beautiful filefish, a blue parrot fish, a ton of grunts and yellow snapper. 
We always release our fish and give back to the ocean. We only take what we will eat which were a few yellow snappers that were delicious with a little butter, salt, pepper and lemon juice. 
This pelican was pretty pissed that we didn't catch anything extra for him though. 
#springbreak #catchandrelease

The community of Louisville is in mourning today for our loved ones and neighbors whose lives were cut short by another senseless shooting.  
@leeinitiative is doing what we can to bring our city together, to begin the healing process and to bring meals and comfort to our EMS workers, police and families who have been affected.  If you know of someone in need please let us know.
I am choosing to focus on celebrating the victims, not identifying or, in any other way, bringing attention to the shooter. I wish the news outlets and others on social media would do the same.  Outside of our morbid curiosity, it does nothing to help the healing process and it could actually inspire the next horrific shooting.  
I choose to focus on healing, on the families of the victims, on our amazing response teams, on gun control, on mental health issues, on safety for us and our families.  On anything other than giving a platform to people who commit unspeakable crimes.  
Much love to Louisville tonight.

This is our doenjang we are making for @namisteakhouse 
It goes into so many dishes from dipping sauces to marinades to soups and stews.  For me it is the backbone of Korean cuisine.  We have experimented with many many versions as I chase the memory of my grandmother's doenjang fermenting on our family's window sill when I was a kid.
Doenjang is a fermented soy bean product silimar to Japanese miso.  In many recipes they are interchangeable but there is a profound difference between the two.  Our doenjang uses no rice or grain, just soy beans, salt (and a few secret ingrediemts) naturally fermented.  It is not as sweet as miso and it is distinct in its course texture.  The umami flavor is profound and it has personality.  Every batch will be a little different and that is part of the importance of making a fermented product from scratch.  We look forward to welcoming you at Nami to taste our first batch of doenjang.

I am proud and thankful to be named the guest chef for the next White House State Dinner welcoming the President and First Lady of South Korea. 
As a chef, I don't stop very often to reflect or take inventory of life but during all the prep and interviews and press conferences, I have been overwhelmed with a feeling of gratitude.  There is so much of my identity that bounces between the worlds of being American and also being Korean.  I am deeply proud of both and I have so much to say about the opportunities that America has offered my family and myself.  To come full circle and offer my services to honor the friendship between these two nations is nothing short of a lifetime pinnacle. 
There are so many I have to thank: my mom, my family, my business partners, my chefs and staff who support me everyday.  To the entire @whitehouse staff who has been so kind to me and especially FLOTUS @flotus  who put so much thought into this momentous event. 
Thank you to @us_protocol and @statedept for your commitment to culinary diplomacy. 
I only wish my Dad were still here to witness this event.  I know he would have been proud.

The opening of @namisteakhouse has been a dream come true and a whirlwind.  Thanks to all who have visited us in our first chaotic week. 
One of our more popular dishes so far has been our Hwe Bibimbap. 
In Korean, bibimbap literally just means "mixed rice" and it is rice in a sizzling crock with a mix of toppings.  I've eaten this dish my whole life and the toppings are generally a mix of spimach, carrots, egg, bean sprouts etc. 
I wanted to create toppings that match the flavor profile of the protein.  So our rare seared salmon bibimbap is paired with watercress, endive, white kimchi, salmon roe and chili.  The beef bibimbap has different toppings and so does the vegetarian bibimbap. 
Each bibimbap is unique and we will change them seasonally as well.
The rice we use is a blend of white rice, browm rice and millet which is an important grain in Korea. 
All of this amounts to a version of bibimbap that is interpreted through a modern lens. And it is delicious.
Thanks to the team at Nami and chef @breannabaker who is making this kitchen run like clockwork.  It is never easy staying calm in the face of a new restaurant opening but our fearless chef is doing it all everyday.

Thank you @nytimes and @kimseverson for including @namisteakhouse in your story about what hospitality looks like today. 
The answer is so complicated and divisive right now but I am committed to bridging what we valued about traditional hospitality with a new version of management that seeks to give workers respect and empowerment. 
When we started the concept for Nami 2 years ago during the pandemic, there were so many unknowns and we didn't know what restaurants would become in 2023.  But the idea of bringing back real hospitality was always front and center.  I am a life long restaurant worker and I believe there is nothing more special than a delicious restaurant with attentive and warm service.  We aren't perfect yet but we strive for this everyday.  It is commitment and belief and months of training. 
If you visit a restaurant and are impressed with the service, please know that it doesn't happen by accident.  A lot of teamwork goes into creating what is a seamless night of service.  Give them some love and tip your waitstaff well.  They are tremendously hard workers who have a passion for hospitality..

One of our most popular desserts on the menu @namisteakhouse is this Ginger infused Shaved Ice with Coconut Condensed Milk, Lychee, Yuja, Ginger Snap Powder and ground Black Sesame Seeds

It's funny because when we developed the Nami menu, @breannabaker and I thought this would be the least popular dessert and it has quickly become a hit with customers. 
Just goes to show you never can predict what will resonate with people.  But I'm so glad it gets to stay on the menu because I eat one every week and it's awesome.

Always fun to see a nice mention about Smoke & Pickles, my first cookbook. And yes it's of course proper to have two copies, one to cook out of and one to sleep with at night. 
Been fun watching The Bear and seeing the reactions from so many who aren't in the restaurant industry.  It's a tough watch and a tough life but I can't imagine any other way to live. And I wouldn't trade it for anything else in the world.
 
And while we're talking about books, I'm finishing up my 3rd book which should be out in spring of next year.  Every book is a long and  unpredictable journey and this one has been a huge commitment. I made a promise to myself a long time ago that I would only write a book if I think I have something relevant to say.  I never want the process to be easy or formulaic.  I'm always nervous about the prospect of sending my written words out into the world.  But as I edit my manuscript for the last time before sending it out to print, I am encouraged by the folks out there who appreciate the work.

It's a heat wave out there Louisville, so make sure you cool down with a few of these refreshing Lychee Martini's @namisteakhouse

Fun story about the origin of the lychee martini that you might now know. 
I started making this cocktail in 1996 when I had a small Asian restaurant called Clay on Mott Street in NYC.  We made it with soju and lychee wine and lychee juice.  It became an overnight sensation and we were selling it by the gallons every night. Now I'm not going to claim I invented it but alot of publications back then attributed the rise of the lychee martini to us and The Difford's Guide @diffordsguide claims it was invented at Clay.  If you Google it, there are alot of versions of the origin of the lychee martini.  They are all fun and they could all be true as it is very possible that different bars could have come up with it independently of each other. 

But it all comes down to this: Life takes a long time to come full circle and so I'm bringing back the lychee martini with a new and awesome recipe by @outer_stace and you should be drinking it now. 

#lycheemartini

Soju is the national drink of South Korea, and it is quickly becoming one of America’s trendiest libations.
But what is soju?? What’s it made from, and what flavors should we look for?
At @namisteakhouse and @neighborsnoodles we’re starting a Soju Mixology Class for anyone who is interested in this fascinating spirit.  @chefedwardlee will lead a class on how to drink and identify soju and how to pair it with foods. And our Nami bartender will teach you how to make unique soju cocktails that you can recreate at home.
Join us on August 30th for this fascinating and fun deep dive into all things soju. The class will meet at the bar @neighborsnoodles. The class is from 5-6:30pm and includes a soju and cocktail tasting plus recipes and instructions for how to make soju drinks at home. Light appetizers will be provided.

$45/person. Space is VERY limited for this event, please email stacie@nami-restaurant.com to reserve your spot!
#soju #sojucocktails #koreanfoodanddrink #nulu #nulubusinessassociation #chefedwardlee #cocktailclass

It's always great to see a dish from @namisteakhouse in the pages of a print magazine.  Thank you @hemispheresforunited and @ellencarpenter11 for the lovely write up.
This is our Korean Dukbokki dish which is both fervently traditional with some added touches that are completely new yet it all makes sense to me. 
We use both traditional rice cakes as well as a version made from mugwort powder which lends an earthy bitterness to the dish. 
The Bear claw fried chicken is exactly what it sounds like, dark meat fried chicken cut in the same way as a bear claw pastry so you get more fried surface area and it is easy to pull apart if you want to share.  We finish the dish with a few pieces of lightly pickled daikon cubes and a smattering of chopped herbs that include parsley, scallion, perilla and dill.  I know dill isn't very Korean but the flavor works so brilliantly here that I couldn't leave it out just because tradition told me it doesn't belong.

This week I was fortunate enough to host @usembassyseoul at @succotashrestaurant  with an incredible group of influencers from all walks of life from South Korea.  It was a beautiful night and though my Korean was rough we managed to tell some fascinating stories of their lives in Seoul and beyond. 

For their visit I made a special menu for them including this risotto, sort of, that typifies how I see the Korean culinary influence here in America.  I made the risotto with arborio rice but also with Korean rice cakes (Duk) each one diligently cut to the size of a rice grain.  We cooked them together so the final result was something familar but also something completely new.  The texture was amazing.  I finished it with Ssamjang, enoki mushrooms, kimchi juice, fried oysters and a light dusting of Parmigiano. 

I was honored to be given a gift of kimchi all the way from Korea by @korea_grandma.  She is an inspiration and her kimchi is second to none.

I'm so excited to share that I'm heading to NYC with @leeinitiative for a series of panels and dinners at @platformbyjbf at Pier 57! The events are a culmination of this year’s Women Culinary and Spirits Program, which aims to give women a path to leadership in the hospitality space. If you’ve been following along since the beginning, you’ve seen the mentees head to externships, visit Louisville for the KY Experience, attend an immersive Pie Camp with @cherylday, cook for @thisisfab, and so much more. To conclude the program, 5 mentors and all 7 mentees will showcase the power of mentorship and female empowerment and serve dishes inspired by a year of growth and career development.

Join us at Platform for a closer look at the magic of WCSP:
1. Fueling the Next Wave of Women in Hospitality (Nov 13): Discussing the power of female mentorship with LEE mentors – Chefs Anne Quatrano (@rutabaga2) of @starprovisions, Silvia Barban (@chefsilviabarban) of @larinabrooklyn, and Kelsey Barnard Clark (@kelseybarnardclark) of @eatkbc
2. Giving Everyone a Seat at the Table (Nov 14): A collaborative dinner from LEE’s Mentors – Reem Assil (@reem.assil) of @reemscalifornia, Anne Quatrano, Silvia Barban, Rhea Buck (@rhea_is_nerdy_about) of @supper.land, and Kelsey Barnard Clark
3. Cooking Up a More Inclusive Industry and Culinary Future (Nov 16): A Capstone Dinner with this year’s WCSP mentees – Chelsea Ballard (@chelseamariex8), An Cao (@phokytchen), Ashley Knight-Williams (@chefashleykw of @imstillhungrydc), Tayler Barnes (@stagenameshade), Eka Soenarko (@ekitajava), Jarina Naone (@kealohamaile of @elponceatl, and Alex Kachakji (alexontherunn) – and Chef Edward Lee (@chefedwardlee)

We hope to see you there! If you’d like to learn more or secure a seat at any of these events, head to the Platform website, linked in @leeinitiative's bio. We’re so grateful to @MakersMark for joining us in NY and to @Audi for helping us make this happen. Huge thank you to our program partners for the continued support: @libbeypro, @westfield1848, @olo_skiptheline, @chefkgear, @toasttab, @monogramappliances, and @richardsrainwater.

This year, I'm going old school candies for our Halloween treats.  Every year I go trick or treating with my kid and while I love me some Kit Kats, it seems like we get 100 pieces of the same 5 candies.  So this year I am committed to giving out some old and forgotten classics.  I had so much fun going down memory lane finding these oldies but goodies. 
Do you remember any of these?  What did I miss? 
I can't believe they still make the Reggie bar. 
Chunky is still one of the best chocolates
Surprisingly they still make candy cigarettes - I didn't buy them! 
Do kids even know these brands? 
Or will the neighborhood kids egg my house for handing out Neccos? 
Happy Halloween!

The Korean word for raw fish is Hwe.  There are many ways in which Korean cuisine can express the delicate flavors of raw fish, not just in sushi. 
We will explore a menu of raw fish in multiple preparations in a new dinner series we are simply calling HWE @namisteakhouse 
The pic here is a Fried Bibimbap Ball where the filling is in the inside of a rice ball that is then wrapped in thinly sliced Ahi Tuna.  The sauce is Gochujang and pear juice.  And the whole thing is topped with Wasabi Tobiko. 

If you would like to have this in your belly along with other Hwe delights, please join us this Tuesday, Jan 16 @namisteakhouse

We make various seasonal kimchi @namisteakhouse but my favorite by far is the persimmon kimchi. 
It is so delicate and surprising.  We start with slightly underripe fuyu persimmons and let them ferment for just a few days to a week but that is all that is needed to develop a rich and complex flavor while still retaining the perfume of its original fruit. 
Sadly, persimmon season is coming to an end so we say good bye to this fermented delight until next year.  But we will have something equally fun to kimchi next.  Any suggestions? 

#kimchi
